# Authoritative for ns-ip-mismatch.demo. The parent (root zone)
# advertises this delegation with NSes ns1 / ns2, BOTH glued to
# 172.31.0.19 (this container). When the exporter queries this
# container for the A records of those same NS hostnames, the zone
# file below answers 172.31.0.20 instead — same NS NAMES, a
# DIFFERENT IP. Exercises #37: the parent's glue and the auth's own
# addresses for its nameservers disagree, so resolvers seeded from
# the parent talk to .19 while resolvers that re-query the auth are
# told .20. Names agree (the NS-name rows pass); only the new
# "Parent glue agrees with auth-reported addresses" row FAILs.
#
# Both .19 (this container, the address the parent glues) and .20
# (coredns-ns-ip-mismatch-b, the address this zone file claims) serve
# this same zone. The exporter reads the zone via the .19 glue, then
# re-resolves the NS hostnames to .20 and probes there — so .20 must
# answer too, or every downstream probe would time out.

ns-ip-mismatch.demo. {
    file /zones/ns-ip-mismatch.demo.zone
    log
    errors
}
